SALMONELLOSIS, SEROTYPE BAREILLY - USA: POSSIBLE SUSHI LINK
***********************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

[1]
Date: Wed 4 Apr 2012
Source: CNN [edited]
http://www.cnn.com/2012/04/04/health/us-salmonella-outbreak/index.html


Federal and state health officials are investigating a salmonellosis outbreak in 19 states and the District of Columbia, according to the CDC. The CDC reports 90 people in 19 states and the District of Columbia have been sickened by _Salmonella [enterica_ serotype] Bareilly. The CDC has not yet released which states are involved. The 1st case report of this particular foodborne illness was reported on 28 Jan 2012. The most recent case was reported Mon 2 Apr 2012.

"CDC is collaborating with public health officials in several states and the FDA to investigate a multi-state outbreak of _Salmonella_ serotype Bareilly infections," CDC spokeswoman Lola Russell said in a statement to CNN.

News of the investigation first surfaced late Tue 3 Apr 2012, when an internal memo was inadvertently sent to everyone at the FDA, according to FDA spokesman Curtis Allen. He says the memo speculates about a possible source of contamination, sushi, but he says the FDA doesn't know the origins of the outbreak at this time.

According to the CDC, state public health officials are interviewing those who became ill to find out what they may have eaten and been exposed to in the week before they got sick. This is the how investigations into foodborne illnesses are typically conducted.

Russell said "on initial interviews, many of the ill persons reported consuming sushi, sashimi, or similar foods in a variety of locations in the week before becoming ill." However, it is still early in the investigation.

According to the CDC, consumers are not being told to avoid any particular food or restaurants. Once a particular food is identified for this outbreak, the public will be notified, according to a CDC statement.

[Byline: Miriam Falco]

