******
[2]
Date: Wed 4 Apr 2012
Source: eFoodAlert [edited]
http://efoodalert.net/2012/04/04/salmonella-bareilly-infects-90-people-update-4412/


At least 90 people in 19 US states and the District of Columbia have been infected with a single outbreak strain of _S._ Bareilly, according to a preliminary report released this morning by CDC.

Many of the confirmed outbreak patients reported consuming sushi, sashimi, or similar foods in a variety of locations in the week before becoming ill. The investigation, CDC says, has not "conclusively identified a food vehicle." This is an ongoing investigation and state public health officials are continuing to interview outbreak victims.

The news leaked yesterday (3 Apr 2012) via a memo that was inadvertently circulated throughout FDA, spokesperson Curtis Allen told JoNel Aleccia of msnbc.com.

A survey of state health agencies, combined with the information contained in the original FDA memo and today's [4 Apr 2012] CDC news release has yielded the following information as of 3 Apr 2012:

Confirmed cases have been reported by Texas, the District of Columbia, Maryland, Rhode Island, Connecticut, Wisconsin, Missouri, New York State, and Louisiana. The remaining 11 states have not yet been identified.

No confirmed cases have been reported, and no suspect cases are currently under investigation, in Alaska, Arizona, Hawaii, Idaho, Iowa, Maine, Minnesota, Nevada, Oklahoma, or Utah.

Restaurant-associated illness clusters were identified in Texas, Wisconsin, Maryland, and Connecticut. Illness clusters of this nature are often instrumental in determining the source of an outbreak strain.

New York State has confirmed 17 cases of _S._ Bareilly, excluding cases that may have been detected in New York City, which is served by its own Department of Health. One of the 17 New York State cases was hospitalized; the victim has since been discharged and is recovering. No additional cases are under investigation by the state's Department of Health.

Louisiana has reported 2 confirmed cases, both of whom were hospitalized and are described as "doing well." No additional cases are under investigation in Louisiana at this time.

New York State spokesman Peter Constantakes declined to comment on the possible association between the outbreak and the consumption of tuna roll sushi, preferring to defer to CDC, which is the lead investigating agency for the outbreak. Louisiana spokesperson Speakes confirmed that 1 of 2 Louisiana victims reported having eaten spicy roll sushi; there was no food history available from the other victim.

While early media reports have pointed an accusing finger at spicy tuna roll sushi, it is too early to conclude that this is the definitive source of the outbreak. Even if the sushi proves to be a common element, FDA will need to carry out a trace-back investigation to determine, if possible, which component of the sushi roll may have been contaminated.

CDC has "no specific advice to consumers" at this time. The public is NOT being advised to avoid any specific foods or restaurants.

